The Mundelein community held a School Supplies Distribution event for area families in need of school supplies to start the new school year. One hundred fifty bags of supplies were distributed to students who attend districts 75, 76 and 120.

The community collected supplies and, in addition, the Mundelein Citizens‚Äô Police Academy Alumni Association, the Mundelein Latino Police Academy Alumni Association and the Mundelein Police Department partnered together and made a $750 donation to the drive. Arnold Krinski, president of the Police Academy Alumni, delivered the check to the group last week.

The Black Student Union of MHS assisted in the distribution efforts. They volunteered the evening of August 27. ‚ÄúThis event would not have been successful without their support,‚Äù said Jamie DiCarlo, assistant superintendent of student services. ‚ÄúThe idea for the event came from Veronica Villasenor, community member and District 120 parent,‚Äù DiCarlo explained.

post_text:
D75 families:

Due to network latency issues we have been experiencing, we changed the configuration on our student Chromebooks to temporarily stop web filtering through the District 75 firewall. This means that student Chromebooks will temporarily not be filtered by the school district. We hope to have this issue resolved by early next week, at which time we will turn filtering back on. Until then, Chromebooks will be reliant on their home network and whatever filtering is already in place.

As always, District 75 encourages safe use of the internet and devices. This includes:

Regularly check in on your child when they are working with their computer or using the internet.

Always be aware of what your child is doing and who they may be communicating with when on their device.

Outside of school hours, encourage your child to use their device where you can closely supervise their activity.

The following parent update was sent today:

Dear Mundelein District 75 Families:

We‚Äôve just finished our first e-learning cycle for April. Cycle 2 begins on Monday. We understand that there are a few issues with Seesaw response mechanisms for our K-2 students. This will require some technical work on the back end of the platform. Please be patient as we work through these issues and know that all the staff at District 75 are here to support your child‚Äôs learning the best we can. Visit the Student Learning Hub for more information about e-learning and answers to frequently asked questions. The hub can be accessed by visiting the district‚Äôs website at district75.org and clicking on the E-Learning Resources button at the top of the home page.

As a reminder, paper materials are only printed for those who do not have WiFi access. As a courtesy to those families, and for your safety, please do not come to the district office to pick up materials if you have WiFi access on a device at your home.

Thank you.

Dan Swartz
Assistant Superintendent for Teaching and Learning

post_text: Items are still needed for the food distribution to Mundelein families. They include: bread, tortillas, beans (dried and canned), canned meats (like tuna and chicken), peanut butter, jelly, pasta, deodorant and toothpaste. They are also looking for new crayons, sharpened pencils, puzzles, coloring books and $10 gift cards to local grocery stores. Dear Mundelein District Families:

I hope this message finds you well. District 75 will continue e-learning until April 30. Beginning tomorrow at 9:00 am, teachers will be reaching out to our preschool - 4th graders through Seesaw and via Google Classroom for our 5th - 8th graders. Paper copies of assignments for those who do not have WiFi access will be available on Friday, April 3 from noon - 6:00 pm at the District Office. More information about e-learning, as well as access to the Student Learning Hub can be accessed from the homepage of our website at www.district75.org.

Thank you for your continued support.

Dr. Kevin Myers
Superintendent

post_text:
Gear up for STEAM Camp 2020 hosted at Mundelein High School coming soon this summer! STEAM Camp 2020, brought to you by Mundelein High School and in partnership with District 75, District 75 STEAM Foundation, District 76 and District 79, is a low-cost opportunity that is open to all current D75 students. At STEAM Camp, campers will get active, hands-on and minds-in with experiences in robotics, 3-D printing, engineering design, cooking, art projects, science experiments, "Escape" rooms, sewing, filmmaking and more!

Rookie Camp: Incoming grades 1-2
Middler Camp: Incoming grades 3-5
Varsity Camp: Incoming grades 6-9

Bus transportation and student scholarships are available for these camps. For a list of camps available, specific dates, times and camp descriptions, or to register (registration opens March 30), please visit www.d120.org/academics/stem. You may also contact Tony Cho, STEAM Camp Coordinator, at acho@d75.org should you have any specific questions regarding STEAM Camp scholarships and/or registration.

The beginning of school is a month away! We are so excited to welcome the students back for the 2019-2020 school year. By the end of July, families will begin receiving information about class placements, schedules, and bussing, as well as, additional plans for kindergarten transition. Until then, here are some key dates for your family calendars.

Remember, the first day of school for students in 1st through 8th grade is August 14th. Kindergarten will begin the following day on August 15th.

Kindergarten Kick-off is August 6th from 5-7.

Mrs. Moulee Gupta
Mr. Mark Pilut

post_text:
Please join District 75‚Äôs 40th Annual Brat Fest at Carl Sandburg Middle School from 5 to 8 p.m. Friday, Sept. 8.

The $5 Brat Fest meal includes roasted corn on the cob, chips, a drink, and choice of bratwurst, hot dog, or tamale.

Carl Sandburg Principal Mark Pilut said, ‚ÄúOur school board members and administrators serve the meals to thank community members for their support of our schools.‚Äù

The District 75 PTO makes the event inviting for children and families by sponsoring face painting, carnival games, a bungee run, and special this year - a mechanical bull.

Carl Sandburg Middle School is located at 855 W. Hawley St., Mundelein. All are welcome!

Village of Mundelein
August 22, 2017 at 2:39 PM ¬∑

Mundelein High School Earns Top 100 Ranking in 2018 Best Public High Schools in Illinois List

Please join Mayor Steve Lentz and the Board of Trustees in congratulating Mundelein High School for earning a ‚ÄúTop 100 High Schools in Illinois‚Äù ranking. For the third year in a row, Mundelein High School is in the top 100 high schools according to Niche. The 2018 Best Public High Schools ranking is based on rigorous analysis of academic and student life data from the U.S. Department of Education along with SAT/ACT test scores, teacher quality, college readiness, graduation rates, and ratings collected from millions of Niche users. This year MHS ranked 76 in Illinois. Last year, MHS ranked 87. During the previous three years, MHS has moved up 16 spots and improved a full letter grade from a ‚ÄúB‚Äù to an ‚ÄúA.‚Äù Congratulations!
